The paper deals with the interplay between features and network link structure, which is a common topic in social network analysis and machine learning. The use of perceptrons and Naive Bayes also suggests a focus on classification and prediction tasks, which are often studied in the sub-categories of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The mention of large-scale networks and the need for scalability points towards cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the use of latent feature-feature interactions and the analysis of real-world datasets suggests a connection to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence).
